ty, and the intersections of identity and law based on the liberal tradition of jurisprudence and transnational influences. Ultimately, Law without Nations offers sharp analyses of the fraught relationship between the nation and the state-and the legal forms and practices that they require, constitute, and violently contest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aInternational and municipal law. 0aLaw and globalization. 0aLaw. 0aNation-state. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh1 aDouglas, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804777223zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777223.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles